Initial commit

Initial import.This is a fork of okhttp from http://code.google.com/p/okhttp.nI'm moving it to Github since that's where my code reviewersnare. I've renamed the core package from com.google.okhttp toncom.squareup.okhttp because Square is where I expect ongoingndevelopment of this project to take place.nnAll code in this project is subject to be contributed upstreamnto AOSP. In particular, all code in the libcore package isnderived from AOSP and intended to be contributed back to AOSPnon an ongoing basis.n

Use bouncy castle to generate certs for TLS.Because there are no platform APIs to generate certificates,nthis needs a third party library (bouncy castle) to do thenheavy lifting.nnEach target platform has its own built-in crypto library:n - The JVM has its own internal crypto library. It usesn   key stores like JCA.n - Android has its own internal crypto library that'sn   based on bouncy castle. It is repackaged in com.androidn   and is not used by this code.nnWith this change, okhttp brings its own copy of bouncy castlenfor cert generation. Once the certificate is generated we'rendone with bouncy castle, and use the platform libraries for TLS.nThis approach allows us to use one codebase on either platform.n
Merge pull request #10 from square/jwilson/sslUse bouncy castle to generate certs for TLS.

Support Froyo.This makes a bunch of sad changes for compatibility:n - Using String.length() rather than String.isEmpty()n - Using String.getBytes(String) rather than String.getBytes(Charset)n - Using new String(..., String) rather than new String(..., Charset)n - Avoiding TimeUnit.DAYSnnI've tested this and the HTTP tests run perfectly fine on Froyo.nThe HTTPS tests time out due to a bug in Froyo that preventsnits TLS library from working as a server. I manually verifiednthat TLS works as a client without problem.nnI also tested this on Gingerbread. It passes all tests exceptnfor testConnectViaHttpProxyToHttpsUsingProxySystemProperty, whichnfails because of a bug in Gingerbread's java.net.ProxySelector.nnThis change introduces caching reflective objects for NPN access.nThat'll make clients that make multiple SSL connections slightlynmore efficient.n

Fail gracefully on a 401 response code with no WWW-Authenticate header.This is more lenient than necessary; the HTTP spec says this:n  10.4.2 401 Unauthorizedn The request requires user authentication. The response MUST include an WWW-Authenticate header field (section 14.47) containing a challengen applicable to the requested resource.nnNot throwing will still cause the request to fail, since the 401nresponse code triggers an IOException. But this type of failure isnmore recoverable and allows the caller to inspect the headers andnresponse body.n
Merge pull request #16 from square/jwilson/authheaderFail gracefully on a 401 response code with no WWW-Authenticate header.

Be more careful about synchronization.SpdyConnection needs to guard its own state separately fromnthe SpdyWriter, which permits slow blocking calls. Split theseninto multiple independent locks.nnAlso use independent right-sized thread pools for reading (exactlynone thread all the time) delayed writing (0 or 1 threads) andncallbacks (any number of threads).n

Abandon foolish consistency with SpdyReader for sending frames.Setting fields and then calling a method is just not as usablenas calling a method that takes arguments.nnAlso move Settings into their own class, so we can sling themnaround without a bunch of ceremony.n

Be strict and careful when parsing the response status line.The current status line parsing is lenient and sloppy; anholdover from an ancient version of this library. The newncode is strict and provides a helpful message if a bogusnstatus line is encountered.nnTo make this possible the RawHeaders class needs a hintnabout whether it's looking for a request line (from annHTTP request) or a status line (from an HTTP response).nThe old sloppy code used the same APIs for both.n
Merge pull request #43 from square/jwilson/strictstatuscodeBe strict and careful when parsing the response status line.

Support noop frames. Make ping sending a blocking (synchronous) call.Although blocking calls don't fit the SPDY model very well, theynmake exception transparency easy. In this case, a NOOP or a PINGnwill throw if it cannot be sent. This is good.n
Merge pull request #44 from square/jwilson/noopSupport noop frames. Make ping sending a blocking (synchronous) call.

Tests and code for various SPDY close scenarios.Writing this change has led me to believe that thenconcurrency here is just plain awful, and I need tonfind a better solution than what I have. In particular,nthere are too many threads:n - the internal reader threadn - application reader threadsn - application writer threadsnAnd too many locks:n - the SpdyWriter I/O write lockn - the SpdyConnection internal state lockn - each SpdyStream's internal state locknnWhat's currently very wrong is the internal reader threadnis updating state in the SpdyStream, and reading bytes fromnthe network into a particular stream. It is an error to holdnthe SpdyStream's lock while reading, but we're doing it becausenwe need to hold the state on the buffer, position and limit.nWe need to rethink this!nnChrome doesn't run into this problem because it can 'fire andnforget' events. We can't do that because SPDY writes need tonthrow IOExceptions if the writes fail.n

Fix a severe bug where multiple TLS tunnels were attempted.The previous code would attempt a TLS tunnel on reusednHTTPS connections, even after the tunnel had been established.nThis is a severe protocol error!n

Fix connection recycling for TLS+gzip+chunked.We had a bug where the underlying SSLInputStream always returnedn0 for InputStream.available(). This prevented us from ever readingnthe end of stream chunk, which prevented connection recycling.nhttp://code.google.com/p/android/issues/detail?id=38817nnAlso fix a nearby bug where we were fast-forwarding the gzippednstream when we should have been fast-forwarding the transfernstream when we were preparing to recycle a connection.n
Merge pull request #48 from square/jwilson/recycle_gzipFix connection recycling for TLS+gzip+chunked.

Make HttpConnection.connect return full working connections.Previously the returned connections required the caller tondo extra work: setting up tunnels (which could require auth)nand performing an SSL handshake. With this change we make ancomplete working connection in HttpConnection.connect().nnThis will make it easier to fix fallback when a single domainnhas multiple IP addresses and some of those addresses are notnreachable.nnThis will also make it easier to do SPDY through HTTP proxies.n
Correct checkstyle errors.

Don't drop out of connect if the first request fails.This fixes a break caused by the recent try-harder-on-IP-addressesnchange, where if the first connect failed we returned rather thanntrying until we reached a connection or an error.n
Merge pull request #54 from square/jwilson/reconnectDon't drop out of connect if the first request fails.

New API to break platform-specific dependencies.In particular:n - Don't require OkHttp to depend on Jetty's non-boot package forn   Android. This was causing ugly, confidence-smashing dalvikn   errors in Android apps.n - Don't prevent HTTP on Java6 just because SPDY isn't available.nnThis uses gross reflection and dynamic proxies! That's sad, butnit's encapsulated so users won't have to know it exists.n
Merge pull request #56 from square/jwilson/platform-apiNew API to break platform-specific dependencies.
Fix checkstyle issues.
Merge pull request #58 from square/jwilson/checkstyleFix checkstyle issues.

Improve connection reuse.Instead of trying to read the last bytes of a content bodynwhen the input stream is read, do it when the connection isnclosed. This approach is less elegant, since it requiresna connection to do work on behalf of a potentially nonexistentnfollow up connection. But it should result in more reuse innpractice.nnhttp://code.google.com/p/android/issues/detail?id=38817n
Merge pull request #59 from square/jwilson/improve_reuseImprove connection reuse.

Switch to a builder for HttpURLConnection instances.The builder has two upsides:n - It allows us to use the same base classes from java.netn   as the base API.n - It gives us a place to stash configuration in a place othern   than static fields. This will be useful for the connectionn   pool, cookie manager, response cache, etc.n
Move out of the libcore package.To promote the code into AOSP, we'll keep this package as-isnand do the jarjar in Android instead.n
Remove some dead code.
Bump the version number for backwards-incompatible changes.
Merge pull request #60 from square/jwilson/aospPrepare to use OkHttp to back HttpURLConnection in AOSP

Move system-wide statics to the OkHttpClient class.This makes it possible to have two HttpClient instances thatndon't share cookies or response cache policy. For example, anprogram that makes both REST calls and downloads images maynprefer different response caches for each type of resource.n

Clean up commented out URLConnection tests.There were some tests that only work on Dalvik/Linux: the CloseGuardntest and the timeout test rely on Linux-specific behavior that's toonflaky for a general test.nnThe TrustManager test just needed some attention and simplification tonwork on both the JDK and Dalvik TLS stacks.n
Merge pull request #62 from square/jwilson/commented_testsClean up commented out URLConnection tests.
Merge pull request #61 from square/jwilson/fewer_staticsMove system-wide statics to the OkHttpClient class.
Move the SSL socket factory and hostname verifier to the client.This saves clients from needing to cast to HttpsURLConnectionnto expose the HTTPS-only accessors.n

Restore tests for response caching + TLS.One of the test cases bitrotted to failure as a consequencenof the HTTP route selector change. I stopped assigning thensocket, which it needed to cache the TLS metadata. This isnfixed.n
Merge pull request #64 from square/jwilson/tls_caching_testsRestore tests for response caching + TLS.
Merge pull request #63 from square/jwilson/fewer_castsMove the SSL socket factory and hostname verifier to the client.

Prepare to promote HttpConnection + Pool to public API.Giving the application code access to the connection poolnis tricky: it exposes more implementation details fromnOkHttp; details that are quite inaccessible through thenconventional HttpURLConnection APIs. Currently the onlynthing regular users get are a pair of awkward systemnproperties.nnBut exposing these should also be useful: it'll allow thenapplication to observe the pool (for performance monitoring)nand possibly also to directly manage it (by setting policy,nor to evict when the application is paused).n
Merge pull request #65 from square/jwilson/connectionPrepare to promote HttpConnection + Pool to public API.
Promote Connection, ConnectionPool and Address APIs.This moves HttpConnection.Address and HttpConnection.TunnelConfignto their own top-level classes.n
Merge pull request #66 from square/jwilson/new_apisPromote Connection, ConnectionPool and Address APIs.

Clean up utility code for submission to AOSP.This moves methods that will have Android-specific implementationsnto Platform.java; all other utility methods are in a junk drawernclass called Utils.java.nnThis also moves method names (like GET) to compare with .equalsninstead of '=='. The old code took advantage of a hidden agreementnbetween HttpURLConnection and HttpEngine; with these in separatenprojects that behavior isn't as obvious and shouldn't be reliednupon.n
Merge pull request #67 from square/jwilson/libcoreClean up utility code for submission to AOSP.
Unsuppress some tests.These were suppressed because they needed a bit ofnwork; I did that work and now they pass.n
Upgrade to JUnit 4.Primary motivation is to gain access to @Ignore, for somentests that haven't yet been written, or that don't work onnthe RI (due to RI bugs).n
Fix synchronization todos in SpdyStream.This code had bugs where ongoing reads could preventnwrites from occurring. This update adds some assertsnto prevent synchronization errors.n
Merge pull request #70 from square/jwilson/synchFix synchronization todos in SpdyStream.
Merge pull request #69 from square/jwilson/junit4Unsuppress tests and upgrade to JUnit 4.
Improve SPDY error handling and concurrency.
Merge pull request #71 from square/jwilson/errorsImprove SPDY error handling and concurrency.
Implement GOAWAY, for clean shutdowns of SPDY connections.Also clean up some SPDY headers and improve error messages.n
Merge pull request #72 from square/jwilson/goawayImplement GOAWAY, for clean shutdowns of SPDY connections.

Discard streams once they're no longer open.This avoids a memory leak; we don't hold onto the input streamnand it's large 64 KiB buffer long after that stream is done.nnIt also allows SpdyConnection to track how many streams arencurrently active. This will allow a follow up change to shutndown connections that don't host any streams.n
Merge pull request #73 from square/jwilson/openDiscard streams once they're no longer open.
Implement SpdyConnection.close().
Merge pull request #74 from square/jwilson/closeImplement SpdyConnection.close().

Make timeouts work for SPDY.We can't use the regular socket timeouts because thensocket is shared. Moving it to the application levelnis more complicated, but it allows different streamsnto set timeouts independently.n
Use TLS + NPN in SpdyServer.This server is able to serve content to Chrome, afterndismissing the 'untrusted server' warning.n
Merge pull request #75 from square/jwilson/timeoutsMake timeouts work for SPDY.

Flatten internal packages and utility classes.The previous structure had hierarchy that was usefulnfor libcore but overkill for OkHttp.n

Implement flow control for the incoming stream.This sends a WINDOW_UPDATE frame whenever the total number ofnunacknowledged bytes exceeds 32 KiB. This is a simple policy;nwe could tune it to be more sophisticated as necessary.nnThis fixes downloads of streams greater than 64 KiB.n

Use an MTU-sized buffer for socket access.Previously we attempted to avoid buffers in some situationsnand create aggressive buffers in other situations. This wasna bad policy, and meant we had some subtle performance bugs.nThe one that prompted this is that chunked uploads makenseparate network writes for the chunk size, chunk, and newlinenseparators.nnThis avoids that problem and the corresponding complexity.nUnfortunately getting the MTU isn't a standard API untilnJava 6 / Gingerbread. I tested my own networks and saw 1500nin use (for 3G and WiFi) and 1400 (for VPN over WiFi).n
Merge pull request #152 from square/jwilson/mtuUse an MTU-sized buffer for socket access.

Recover from failures while writing a POST body.This introduces failure recovery in the output stream. It meansnwe should be able to recover from any kind of failure that couldnbe triggered by aggressive connection pooling.nnThe recovery buffer is 8 KiB. I anticipate this should be morenthan enough to detect that an HTTP post is going to a black hole.n

Use one callback for SYN_STREAM, SYN_REPLY and HEADERS.This is closer to the semantics of HTTP/2.0, which uses the HEADERSnframe for all three types. SPDY is a bit more strict because itnrelies on redundancy; it's an error to send a SYN_REPLY after anHEADERS frame. With HTTP/2.0, there's only one type so there'snno error to detect.n

Upstream changes made directly to AOSP.This change is a combination of 4 separate commitsnto fix various bugs observed during android platformntesting.nnhttps://android-review.googlesource.com/#/c/63781/n--------------------------------------------nAllow certificate inspections after connect.nnWe don't have to wait for the request to be sentnbefore allowing inspection of SSL certs. They can beninspected as soon as the connection is established.nnFixes CTS test UrlConnectionTest#testInspectSslAfterConnectnnhttps://android-review.googlesource.com/#/c/63821/n---------------------------------------------nRespect read timeout on recycled connections.nnPartial fix for CTS test : URLConnectionTest#testGetKeepAlive.nnhttps://android-review.googlesource.com/#/c/63782/n-----------------------------------nFix HttpUrlConnection#isUsingProxy.nnThe earlier implementation disregarded what thenProxySelector had to say. We now query the selectednroute (if one has been established).nnFixes compatibility test:nHttpURLConnectionTest#testUsingProxySelectornnhttps://android-review.googlesource.com/#/c/63872/n--------------------------------------------nDon't support anything other than Basic auth.nnWe should disregard authentication schemes other thannBasic and let clients handle them themselves.nnThe java Authenticator API gives us a user name andnpassword combination, but we can't know how to formatnthat information for any scheme other than basic.nnHistorically:nnThe JB implementation responds to challenges from annarbitrary scheme X by sending a header with schemenX but formatted like the Basic scheme.nnThe current implementation responds to challenges fromnan arbitrary scheme X by sending a header with schemenBasic and formatter like the Basic scheme.nnPartial fix for test cases in URLConnectionTest:n- testAuthenticateWithCommaSeparatedAuthenticationMethodsn- testAuthenticateWithMultipleAuthenticationHeadersn

Define async APIs and switch Job to use HttpEngine directly.Using HttpEngine directly introduces some duplicated code withnHttpURLConnection. It also breaks the response cache. Introduce Handshake as a value object.I needed a non-terrible way to provide the HTTPS handshakeninformation to the async API. Previously we were passing thenlive socket around, which was leaky and gross.nnThis creates a new value object that captures the relevantnbits of the handshake. We can use it in the response, thenconnection, and also in the cache. It's plausible that innthe future we can use it to allow the application to blocknrequests if the handshake is insufficient.n

Make RawHeaders, RequestHeaders and ResponseHeaders immutable.This introduces a new, poorly-named class ResponseStrategynthat pulls some code out of ResponseHeaders. Merge pull request #380 from square/jwilson_1229_immutable_headersMake RawHeaders, RequestHeaders and ResponseHeaders immutable.

Combine Request+RequestHeaders and Response+ResponseHeaders.This cleans up a lot of the unnecessary moving parts innHttpEngine. That class is still stuck with some complexitynaround request and response bodies, but it's getting better.nnWe're also stuck escalating the visibility of a lot ofnmembers in Request and Response. I've got some ideas onnhow to fix this; that'll have to wait for a follow up.n
Merge pull request #381 from square/jwilson_1229_requestheadersCombine Request+RequestHeaders and Response+ResponseHeaders.

Move request line and status line out of RawHeaders.The request line is now standalone because it dependsnon the proxy (for full URL or not) and the connectionn(for HTTP version). I may change this later and putnthis info in the request.nnThe status line now moves into Response. I have anhelper class StatusLine that does the parsing. I maynlater want to hide this or make it public; I'm notnquite sure yet!nnThe net result is that RawHeaders is getting dumbernand used in fewer places, which is good news. Thisnchange also shows nice simplifications to thenauthenticator (which needs fewer args) and to thentunnel builder.nnAlso fold together HttpsEngine and HttpEngine; thenHTTPS subclass wasn't pulling its weight.n
Merge pull request #382 from square/jwilson_1230_requestlineMove request line and status line out of RawHeaders.

Remove more stuff from Policy.Policy is a bridge to get us from a place where HttpEnginendepends 100% on HttpURLConnection to a place where itndoesn't.nnWe've refactored the code in HttpEngine enough now thatnsome Policy methods are no longer necessary. Delete 'em.n

OkBuffer API sketch.I'm unhappy with java.io:n * No timeouts.n * Every layer needs to copy bytes around. Always copying bytes.n * Features like mark/reset and available() are clumsy.n * Its awkard in mixed text/binary protocols like HTTP becausen   character decoding is separate and takes over the stream.nnUnfortunately java.nio isn't better, just different:n * It's complex.n * Buffers are fixed size.n * No built-in buffer pooling.n * Features like mark/reset/position are clumsy.nnThis is an obnoxious attempt at a 3rd I/O interface, mostlyninspired by InputStream and OutputStream, but using growablenbuffers instead of byte arrays as the core data container.n

Split HttpTransport in two.The new (awkwardly-named) HttpConnection class now owns thensocket, and stays around between HTTP requests. Move connection pooling logic.Previously we had this ugly, awkward release() method thatnattempted to manage connection pooling, discarding streamsnfor caching, and closing broken streams.nnMove connection reuse to HttpConnection, with policy informednby HttpEngine. It specifies what to do when the connectionnbecomes idle: pool, close or hold. The connection does whatnit's told.n

Return HttpResponseCache to previous (e.g. KitKat) behaviorThis change required to handle this Android scenario:nnWhen this version of OkHttp is packaged into Android in a futurenrelease (in com.android.okhttp...) there is a possibility thatnan older version of OkHttp bundled with applicationn(in com.squareup.okhttp...) will pick up the newer HttpResponseCachenvia ResponseCache.getDefault(). It will attempt to use the get() / put()nmethods. Commit e2599be9e073f1be8e929597c358e2664ab0c9a9 wasnintended to restore HttpResponseCache get() and put() and avoid thenUnsupportedOperationException that would be thrown.nnUnfortunately, it didn't quite do it:nnIn KitKat and older versions OkHttp, in HttpResponseCache the behaviornwas to ignore any calls to put(URI, URLConnection) includingnany HttpURLConnection/HttpsURLConnection that wasn't its ownn(i.e. only ones from com.android.okhttp would be cached). The previousnfix to HttpResponseCache re-introduced get()/put() but didn't implementnthe necessary instanceof checks.nnJesse also informs me that coexistance with other implementationsnof HttpURLConnection is not required (since OkHttp replaces thenHTTP implementation on the desktop). I have also since discoverednthat HttpResponseCache didn't implement the cache-control logicnrequired to follow the letter of the Java API anyway, which meansnthat HttpResponseCache is not suitable for use in cases wherenthe Http(s)URLConnection implementation expects a fully compliantnimplementation.nnAlso addressed nits from e2599be9e073f1be8e929597c358e2664ab0c9a9.n

Fix two problems with the window size.Each peer has a window size. The peer's window size controls how muchndata we can send the peer, and our window size controls how much datanthe peer can send us. We had these reversed in SpdyStream, so if thenpeer specified a non-default window size we wouldn't send the requirednWINDOW_UPDATE events when we needed to.nnThe connection has its own window size. Allow callers to pass in a custom host resolver implementation.An HTTP client interacts with the network in two main ways: DNSnlookups and connections to HTTP servers. OkHttp already abstractsnthe latter by allowing callers to pass in custom SocketFactorynobjects, but does not yet abstract the former.nnThis change takes the existing internal Dns interface, which isncurrently used for testing, and turns it into a publiclynaccessible HostResolver interface. This allows callers toncompletely abstract all network interaction points.nnExamples of what this can be used for:nn1. Use alternative DNS implementations with differentn   performance / caching / ordering / parallelization / ...n   characteristics than standard InetAddress.getAllByName.n2. Resolve hosts using different DNS servers than the systemn   resolvers, or even non-DNS protocols (e.g., MDNS or evenn   NetBIOS/WINS) that are not supported by the system resolver.n3. Do DNS lookups on specific networks, similarly to whatn   android_getaddrinfofornet does.nnChange-Id: I6e488acd938067e4c078c6ffe4d5eddb5f3951den

Update MultipartBuilder to support content length.In order to track content length we need to convert the headers and boundary of a part to a Buffer eagerly. Modify bad CONNECT handlingChanging the way that OkHttp handles CONNECT responsesnfrom proxies.nnBefore the change:nIf a proxy returns a body and some of the body bytes havenalready been buffered then an IOException is thrown.nIf the body bytes have not been buffered then the handshake willnfail due to the presence of bytes where the Server HELLO isnexpected, typically with some kind of SSLHandshakeException.nnAfter the change:nThe body bytes are consumed to ensure consistent behavior. Thenhandshake will then take place.nnHistory:nThis is an unusual case that would occasionally cause failuresnon Android when a ResponseCache was installed. Android introducedna patch to prevent CONNECT responses being cached. Since then,nOkHttp has changed the code and probably fixed the issue vianother means. The Android test remained and would sometimesnexperience one exception, sometimes another, depending on thenstate of the buffer.nnIf the presence of a body is a possibility it would be nicento deal with it consistently and deterministically.nnThe motivation for this change is to makenURLConnectionTest#connectViaHttpProxyToHttpsUsingBadProxyAndHttpResponseCachenbehave consistently and in a way that doesn't involve connectionnfallback.nnThe only risk with this change is if a proxy is incorrectlynreporting the content length: this might lead to blocking onnthe body read/skip (as OkHttp would probably do elsewhere if anserver mis-reports a content-length). This change may makenconnections to bad proxies slightly more reliable.n

Avoid a reverse DNS-lookup for a numeric proxy addressWhen the proxy was specified as an IP address the RouteSelector would forcena reverse-lookup. This introduced extra latency when the DNS is being slow ornmissing. It also then turned the name back into a set of IPs, which couldnresult in the original IP address not being given priority andnconnection attempts being made to IPs besides the one specified by thenoriginal Proxy specifier.nnThis change distinguishes between whether the proxy InetSocketAddress isnspecified with a string, or with an InetAddress. This is referred to asnunresolved and resolved respectively. If an InetAddress is presentnwe assume we should use that single address to communicate with thenproxy.nnThis relies on the InetSocketAddress being created unresolved: if thenInetSocketAddress is created from a hostname but created resolved,nthe InetAddress is filled in and OkHttp will interpret that as anninstruction to just communicate with just that one IP.n
Merge pull request #1186 from nfuller/AvoidProxyReverseLookupAvoid a reverse DNS-lookup for a numeric proxy address

Strict, modern HostnameVerifier.This brings OkHostnameVerifier up to date with the intersection ofnRFC 2818 and Baseline Requirements, and adds support for absolutendomain names.nnThe changes are:n* Absolute domain names are supported. All presented hostnames aren  treated as absolute domain names. All domain names in servern  certificates are treated as absolute domain names as well.n* Wildcard character (*) is permitted only in the left-most domainn  name label and must be the only character in that label. Forn  example, *.example.com is permitted, while *a.example.com,n  a*.example.com, a*b.example.com, a.*.example.com are not permitted.n* Wildcard character (*) must match exactly one domain name label.n  For example, *.example.com matches www.example.com, but does notn  match example.com or www.test.example.com.n* Wildcard pattern cannot mach single-label domain names: * and *.n  patterns are rejected.nnThis is a cherry-pick of the Android Open Source Project (AOSP) changenhttps://android-review.googlesource.com/#/c/117462/.nnFixes #1165n

Fix for a socket leak in OkHttp on AndroidWhen the preferred Android network changes fromncell -> wifi or wifi -> cell the HTTP connectionnpool in use is abandoned to avoid reuse ofnconnections on the old network. This was addednin commit 8bced3e.nnThe design for the connection pool was such thatncontinuous use of the connection pool was required tonclean up idle / expired connections. If a connectionnpool becomes idle (as when it is dereferenced on annetwork change) it is possible for some connectionsnto remain in the pool indefinitely.nnAfter the preferred network change, because the oldnconnection pool was no longer referenced the poolnwould be garbage collected and Android's Strict Modenwould complain about sockets not being closed.nnThe only existing way to avoid this was to callnevictAll(), which would have had issues when anlarge number of connections were returned to the poolnafter evictAll() was called. It also wouldn't worknfor SPDY connections which are shared but not referencencounted, which makes knowing whether it is safe tonclose them difficult.nnThe cleanModeRunnable serves two purposes:nn1) While scheduled / executing, it pins the connectionnpool in memory to avoid it being garbage collected.n2) It continues to close connections (safely) until thenpool is empty.nnIf a connection is then added back to the pool thencleanModeRunnable is restarted.n

Refactoring: Make RouteSelector independent of ConnectionUltimate goal: to improve the TLS fallback behavior so thatnsocket connections will not be created if the necessarynTLS protocols will not be supported.nnTo achieve this RouteSelector will be moved into Connectionnand so that it can be passed the Socket or protocol informationnduring the route selection process.nnThis is a small first step: Make RouteSelector independentnof Connection so that it can later be moved inside ofnConnection. It puts the RouteSelector interface in termsnof Routes, which seems logical.n
Merge pull request #1298 from square/jw/no-one-used-thisRemove old SSL protocol method.

Modify the cipher suite / TLS version selection behaviorMotivation 1: Cipher selection and TLS protocol version selectionnshould be performed over enabled, not support values. Otherwise,nciphers / protocols that are disabled by default are re-enabled.nAndroid would like to avoid enabling values that are considered unsafenand are disabled by the platform, apps or GMS core.nnMotivation 2: Opinionated cipher suite selection makes sense fornOkHttp when bundled with apps. OkHttp probably has the best/newestninformation available when compared with the socket factory itnencounters.nnHowever, with the Android platform usecase the socket factory (i.e.none from the platform, from GMS core, or installed by the app) mightnhave better information (or reasons why specific suites should not benused and so it modifies the enabled set). Android would thereforenprefer OkHttp to select from a default set specified by the socketnfactory, not a list hard-coded at release time.nnUnlike ciphers, for protocols there is no current need tongo with the default enabled set so supporting null / use defaultnis not required for protocols.nnOther change:nnThe ConnectionSpec caching (see supportedSpec) has been removed fromnConnectionSpec. This seems like an risky optimization to me in annenvironment where different SocketFactory instances could be encounterednand doing it properly seems costly and of limited benefit.n
Merge pull request #1297 from square/jw/mock-headersUse 'Headers' in recorded response.

TLSv1 supports TLS extensions so they should be enabledFollow up to:nhttps://github.com/square/okhttp/pull/1196.nnCombined with an NPN bug (18705877) on Android this is thenreason why fallback connections started failing on Androidnafter the COMPATIBLE_TLS was changed to be TLSv1.nn[The NPN bug means that once enabled on a socket from annSSLContext then NPN must be configured for every subsequentnsocket otherwise some of the NPN state will still be set,nbut some will be missing, leading to negotiation issues].nnThe implication of this change is that the follow up requestnafter a handshake failure may now be HTTP/2 or SPDYn(or HTTP/1.1). Previous to this change they would alwaysnhave been HTTP/1.1.nnPrevious to pull 1196 they would also have beennHTTP/1.1 because COMPATIBLE_TLS was SSLv3.n

Move TLS retries / fallback into Connection.API changes:n1) Added: Address.getCertificatePinner()n2) Incompatible API change: Address constructor no longernincludes ConnectionSpecs. Removed getConnectionSpecs().n3) Added: ConnectionSpec.isCompatible(SSLSocket)n4) Added: TlsVersion.javaName()nnImplicit / semantic / internal changes:nn1) Connection now handles all attempts to connect via a routen(effectively a {proxy, socket address} pair), rather than justnone attempt. i.e. Connection now handles all the TLS negotiationnfallbacks internally.nn2) Route no longer deals with TLS versions. Individual TLSnfailures are not counted against a Route. If no connectionnattempts to a route were successful the failure is countednagainst the route.nn3) The code makes a distinction between when variousnIOExceptions occur, with the intention making retries a bitnsmarter. It is now more obvious which exceptions happen duringnsetup (RequestException), connection (RouteException),nHTTP communication and thus which can be retried and whethernthe request might have been sent.n

Squashed commit of the following:make the DiskLruCache's initialize() public through the Cache interfacennThe DiskLruCacheu00e2u0080u0099s cache does lazy initialization. The time spent inninitialization varies depending on the actual cache size and journalnfile size.nnOn very low end device, the initialization time could be as long asn1000 ms once the cache reaches 100M for example on a 4.0 device. Thisnhas significant performance impact on the very 1st cache hit.nnSo the proposed solution is to give the developer an opportunity tonexplicitly do the initialization early on and in a back ground thread.nWithout this change, the developer would have to call any method fromnthe Cache class to warm up the cache implicitly.n

It's simpler.nnhttps://github.com/square/okhttp/issues/1459n

Make call canceling more reliable.We had a bug where the socket-being-connected wasn't being closed when thenapplication used Call.cancel(). The problem is that the SocketConnector modelnassumes the Connection doesn't want a Socket instance until it's fullynconnected.nnThis moves the SocketConnector code back into Connection, removes a lot ofnnested try/catch blocks, and assigns a Socket instance as soon as its created.nnThis also likely fixes some bugs where sockets weren't being closed whennan IOException or RouteException was thrown during connection. Now we alwaysnclose at the top level of connect() unless the connection is successful.nnhttps://github.com/square/okhttp/issues/1779n

Partially revert connection timeout behaviorRelated to issue #1790.nnIf there is a *connection* timeout the next route shouldnbe tried. Timeouts during a request/response shouldnprobably not be retried.nnThe timeout/interrupt behavior was changed in PR #1257nfor issue #1146. This modified both connection andnrequest/response behavior. The issue reported was actuallynabout the use of Thread.interrupt(), not timeouts, but thenbehavior change modified both behavior for interrupt andntimeout.nnPR #1388 split the handling of exceptions so that separatencode now handles connection errors from that which handlesnrequest/response errors. It faithfully kept the behaviornfrom PR #1257.nnThe modification of the timeout behavior during *connection*ncaused problems on Android. Now that the two types of errornhandling are split it's possible to deal with themndifferently and return the connection behavior to tryingnthe next route. This does not modify behavior duringnrequest/response.n

Fix URLConnectionTest.writeTimeouts with large receive buffersThe test relies on small client send / server receive buffersnto force blocking and generate a timeout.nnThe switch to make MockWebServer a @Rule (commitn785d9e94387f404f571775a49c3a9438508bb659) moved thenMockWebServer.start() call earlier in the test execution.nSetting the ServerSocketFactory became a no-op so the servernreceive buffer size was left as the default.nnThe test became reliant on either:n1) The default server socket receive buffer being small enoughn(e.g. less than the data being transmitted).n2) The device being too slow to send the requested data in thentime allowed.nnThe test was recently made less reliable by:n1) The okio commitnf30955cb15eb234f874dd55819686832c960765b, which made the segmentnsize bigger (increasing throughput / transfer efficiency).n2) The OkHttp commit f30955cb15eb234f874dd55819686832c960765b,nwhich reduced the amount of data being sent in the test fromn16MB to 2MB.n3) Recent Android devices have large default buffer sizes. e.g.nNexus 5: 1MB, Nexus 5X: 6MB.n

Fix HTTP/2 bug where we were using SPDY/3 style header concatenation.When multiple headers have the same value in SPDY/3, they are concantenatednand separated by u0000.nnWhen multiple headers have the same value in HTTP/2, they are each writtennindependently.nnThis fixes the problem and rearranges the code to share less behavior thannpreviously. Drop the global static shared connection pool.Instead each new instance of OkHttpClient gets its own connection pool byndefault. This makes the OkHttpClient instances a little more heavyweightn(in that two different instances yield two different connection pools, whichnmeans two different cleanup threads) but it also means there's less weirdnstate sharing between instances.nnOne drawback of this is that if an application wants to immediately freenresources from an OkHttpClient it must call getConnectionPool().evictAll(),notherwise the connection pool thread will remain alive for 5 minutes.n

Change CookieJar to deal with Cookies, not Headers.There's a big consequence to this for compatible with RFC 2965 Cookies. In particular,nthis drops our ability to support 'Set-Cookie2' headers, and some features used therenincluding quoted attributes like 'Max-Age=25'. This is the right move for interop withnbrowsers, and likely to make things better for application developers, but somenpeople who strictly followed the RFC 2965 spec will be broken. (That spec was nevernseriously adopted anywhere, which is the entire motivation of RFC 6265.)nnThe upside is the CookieJar interface is now much more straightforward. This isnparticularly good going forward, and for clients who don't have to worry about thenstrangeness of things like $Version=1 in the RFC 2965 spec.n
Merge pull request #2176 from square/jwilson_1230_new_cookie_apiChange CookieJar to deal with Cookies, not Headers.

Don't do health checks on brand new connections.This is imperfect, but it should save some unnecessary work and willnhopefully prevent RouteSelector from attempting a route when none isnavailable.nnhttps://github.com/square/okhttp/issues/2151n
Merge pull request #2180 from square/jwilson_1231_health_checks_iiDon't do health checks on brand new connections.

Add an accessor to get a Call's Request.In a follow up I'm going to drop support for canceling calls based onntheir tag. Instead, dispatcher might be able to just expose all of thenin-flight calls, and the application layer can loop over those andncancel based on tags or other criteria.n

Another approach to handling strange interceptor bodies.The previous approach Just Works if users have fancy or interesting interceptorsnthat genuinely need to swap the response body in an interceptor and keep thenoriginal body.nnOne problem with that solution is that although it gives expert users a powerfulnway to separate response bodies, it also allows normal users to accidentally leaknresponse bodies in their interceptors.nnThis is an alternate solution that forbids the expert use case and requires thatnclosing the response body stream also closes the underlying socket stream. Itnthrows an exception if that implicit contract is not honored.nnI'm fine with either solution but think we should consider both.n

Recover from REFUSED_STREAM errors in HTTP/2.This implements the following policy:nn - If a REFUSED_STREAM error is received, OkHttp will retry the same streamn   on the same socket 1x.n - If any other error is received, or an additional REFUSED_STREAM error isn   received, OkHttp will retry on a different route if one exists.nnWe may want to follow up by going through HTTP/2 error codes and decidingna per-code retry policy, but this should be good enough for now.nnCloses: https://github.com/square/okhttp/issues/2543n

A Pipe.This is something we need to implement HttpURLConnection atop the nativenOkHttp API. The application thread wants to be active, writing to itsnOutputStream. But in OkHttp's API, this work wants to happen in thenRequestBody.writeTo() callback. To make this work we give the HttpUrlConnectionnOutputStream the sink end of the pipe, and the RequestBody the source endnof the pipe. It's a bit of plumbing, but the benefit is that backpressure,ntimeouts, and failures will propagate as expected.n
Merge pull request #2638 from square/jwilson.0618.pipeA Pipe.

Let SocksProxy use the same definition of localhost as MockWebServer.This fixes SocksProxyTest failing on some systems. The problem was thatnMockWebServer is listening on InetAddress.getByName(localhost) butnSocksProxy was trying to connect to InetAddress.getLoopbackAddress().nThis is not guaranteed to work, for example on recent AOSP, localhostnresolves to 127.0.0.1 but getLoopbackAddress() is ::1 (IPv6).nnThis CL makes the simplest change to make the two consistent so thatnSocksProxyTest passes. In the long run, OkHttp may want to considernusing getLoopbackAddress().getHostname() everywhere instead of hardncoding the hostname localhost at all.n

Reduce memory requirements for MockWebServerTest.disconnectHalfway().MockWebServer.readRequest() was accumulating the request body (1 GByte)ninto an unbounded buffer held in memory. This caused the test to failnwith an OutOfMemoryError on low-memory devices. Due to the OOME, notneven a stacktrace was available.nnThis CL introduces setBodyLimit() to limit the amount of data held innmemory. Note that this is similar to the call to setBodyLimit(0) thatnalready exists in URLConnectionTest.veryLargeFixedLengthRequest().n
Merge pull request #2643 from 15characterlimi/mockwebservertestReduce memory requirements for MockWebServerTest.disconnectHalfway().

Let CipherSuites have arbitrary names.This allows Handshake to accept CipherSuite names that do not have ancorresponding predefined instance in CipherSuite.java, including onesnthat conscrypt uses today or might use in future.nnThe following OkHttp 3 APIs are not changed by this CL:nn - ConnectionSpec still uses Strings to represent CipherSuites for now.nn - CipherSuites are interned (value equality is based on objectn   equality) in order to not break clients that use ==.nnThis CL does introduce these API and behavioral changes:n - CipherSuite instances constructed via CipherSuite.forJavaName(TLS_ + s)n   will now always be different from CipherSuite.forJavaName(SSL_ + s)n   for all possible values of s. Previously, there were 19 specificn   values of s for which those would have yielded equal instances.n - Since CipherSuite is no longer an enum, it no longer extends Enum,n   no longer has name() or valueOf() methods, and no longer implementsn   Serializable.nnChange-Id: I9a544e1c0a51848d492883b3c9b4579899e2744an

Relay. This is a single entry in the upcoming DiskLruCache2.At the moment there are some things still incomplete:n - Timeouts. Not yet tested, and no great implementation plan.n - Thread interrupts. This has been quite problematic forn   the original DiskLruCache. We should test and support thisn   in Relay.n - File system problems. If the host file system is full or notn   accepting writes, we should fallback gracefully. This mayn   be difficult.n - Metadata updates. At the moment the metadata is permanentn   and immutable.nnThat said, many nice features are already implemented:n - Metadata and stream data in one file.n - No locks held during file I/O or network I/O.n - Read from the buffer, the file, or the socket in that order.n - Reference counting on open sources. It is assumed that then   creator of each Relay will take a source, and that guaranteesn   that the count will always reach 0.n

Fix Connection sharing across equivalent OkHttpClientsFixes https://github.com/square/okhttp/issues/2757nnThe OkHttpClient(Builder) constructor and both overloads ofnOkHttpClient.Builder.sslSocketFactory() set a new CertificateChainCleanerninstance on the OkHttpClient.nnBefore this CL, CertificateChainCleaner, CertificatePinner andnTrustRootIndex used object rather than value identity semantics. Thisncaused Address.equals() to not recognize when addresses were equivalent,nwhich broke connection pooling across OkHttpClient instances.nnThis CL changes CertificateChainClaner, CertificatePinner andnTrustRootIndex to use value equality by overriding equals() and hashCode().nnCertificatePinner.pins and BasicTrustRootIndex.subjectToCaCerts's valuesnhave changed from List to Set because their order shouldn't matter.nThis CL uses LinkedHashSet, although HashSet should also work.n

HUC regression test: disconnect in the middle of connecting.Prior to commit 084b06b48bae2b566bb1be3415b6c847d8ea3682 (OkHttp 3.4.0),na HttpURLConnection.disconnect() in the middle of connecting caused anninfinite loop. HUC does not claim to be thread safe, but concurrentndisconnect should generally be supported (it is supported by HttpEngine)nand this bug occurred even when the disconnect() happened in the samenthread, e.g. through the CookieJar.nnThe infinite loop prior to that CL occurred becausen - The loop in HttpURLConnectionImpl.java:418 did not check for then   disconnected state,n - {StreamAllocation,RetryAndFollowUpInterceptor}.recover() returnsn   true for canceled StreamAllocations/calls, butn   StreamAllocation.newStream() immediately fails if already canceled.nnThis bug was specific to HUC and did not affect the Call API becausenRetryAndFollowUpInterceptor's (and, in earlier OkHttp versions,nCall.getResponse()'s) infinite loop did check the canceled casenbefore proceeding.nnThe bug existed since at least OkHttp 2.7.5, likely introduced byncommit c358656c8799d30fd422448153e99a5dd37e298a (OkHttp 2.7.0).nnThe new test asserts that a disconnect() while constructing thencookie headers leads to the new connection being aborted. It wouldnalso be permissible for the connection to succeed (as long as itndoesn't deadlock like it used to), but the stricter test seemsnreasonable to ensure that any behavior change is deliberate.nA disconnect() while accessing the Cache FileSystem has the sameneffect, but this is not covered by the added test because annew FileSystem wrapper class that delegates all calls wouldncreate code maintenance overhead.n

Do not fall back to COMPATIBLE_TLS (TLSv1) by default.Insecure TLS version fallback is a compatibility workaround to connectnto servers that do not implement TLS protocol version negotiationncorrectly; it is vulnerable to man-in-the-middle-attacks (POODLE).nSupport for TLS version fallback was removed in Firefox 37 (Mar 2015)nand Chrome 50 (Apr 2016). As of late 2015, fewer than 0.01% of webnservers relied on protocol fallback.nnAfter this commit, OkHttp still supports TLS version fallback, but itnis now opt-in rather than opt-out.nnExisting tests for fallback functionality were modified to opt-innto the fallback; new tests in CallTest and URLConnectionTestnassert that no fallback happens by default (when not opted-in).n

Fail HTTP/2 connections if the pong is not received. (#3878)This removes the Ping abstraction from our http2 package. This was written asrnif it were a public API, but never exposed to any callers but tests. Removingrnit makes it easier to lock down how pings are used.rnrnThis also removes the NullServer class, replacing it with a new SocketPolicyrnon MockWebServer. The new SocketPolicy, STALL_SOCKET_AT_START, allows us torndo TLS and negotiate an HTTP/2 connection without actually building a properrnHttp2Connection and without responding to pings.rnrnThe behavior in HTTP/2 connections is modeled after our behavior in web sockets.rnWe count outgoing pings, incoming pongs, and confirm that the pongs are keepingrnup. If later we make this policy more sophisticated we can track the changesrnin both places.rnrnCloses: https://github.com/square/okhttp/issues/3261

Fix flaky URLConnectionTest.serverShutdownOutput testThere are usually 2 requests sent to '/b' during the test:n#1 on the busted connection, attempting reusen#2 on a new connectionnnOn successful runs, the server recorded #1 and then #2 and added them to the queue in that order.nnOn failed runs, the server started reading request #1 before #2, but there was a context switch, and it finished reading #2 before #1, recording them in that order. Since #1 was the last to be recorded, the test incorrectly used it to assert that the sequence number was 0. Since #1 was the second to be received on the busted connection, it had a sequence number of 1 so the test failed.nnThe fix removes the assumption that #2 is the last to be recorded.nnFixes https://github.com/square/okhttp/issues/4140.n

Assert connection pool eviction in HttpOverHttp2Test.tearDown()While investigating https://github.com/square/okhttp/issues/4470, I noticed there are sometimes connections left in the pool after calling ConnectionPool.evictAll() in HttpOverHttp2Test.tearDown(). As a result, tests that assume the connection pool is initially empty can appear flaky while the blame is in previous tests, making it hard to debug, and possibly hiding a connection leak bug.nnSo far I've noticed the new assertion fails (very rarely) when tearing down these tests:n* recoverFromMultipleCancelReusesConnectionn* emptyDataFrameSentWithEmptyBodyn* gzippedResponseBodynnThis change may increase flakiness in the short term, but will make it easier to debug, by blaming the right tests.n

Ensure streams are removed from connection within test lifetimeAfter the recent fix, if the call is canceled while writing request headers, the stream is eventually removed from the connection. But this is done on a separate thread, and there was previously no guarantee that it would happen before tearDown() is called and the connection pool is evicted, preventing the connection from being evicted before the next test starts.nnTogether with https://github.com/square/okhttp/pull/4492, this will hopefully fix https://github.com/square/okhttp/issues/4470.n

Fix connection leak if WebSocketListener.onOpen() throwsIf WebSocketListener.onOpen() throws, failWebSocket() is responsible for releasing the allocated streams. Delay loading default ServerSocketFactory until neededServerSocketFactory.getDefault() will load the default JVM truststoren(typically from jre/lib/security/cacerts) as configured by JSSEnsystem properties.nnHowever, a typical use case for setting a custom ServerSocketFactory isnthat the client application has loaded custom keystore or truststorenmaterial into their JVM, usually by creating a custom SSLContext.nnThere's strictly no reason to initialize the default ServerSocketFactorynuntil the mockwebserver has been started, allowing custom settings of thenfactory by clients and avoiding the default load attempt during classnconstruction.nnThis patch simply moves the initiatlization logic into the private startnmethod to avoid the premature loading of trust store materials.n

Make recoverFromCancelReusesConnection() more deterministicThis addresses the following observed failure modes and reduces the flakinesss of the test:nn1. On most runs, the first request is canceled before the client starts to read the response body. In some runs, it's canceled after the client starts to read the response body and the first call doesn't fail as expected.nn2. The first request is sometimes canceled before the server dequeues the first mocked response. That response, which is set to send a body after a 10 second delay, is then used to respond to the second request, which triggers the 5 second test timeout.nnhttps://github.com/square/okhttp/issues/4633n

Fix flaky DuplexTest.duplexWithRedirectThe test is flaky because the server sometimes acts on the 301 response and resets the stream before the action added by MockDuplexResponseBody.sendResponse() is executed. This action then fails because it tries to write to a reset stream. mockDuplexResponseBody.awaitSuccess() then throws and fails the test.nnThe change enforces the de-facto sequence on most runs, where the 301 response is handled only after the Duplex response is sent.nnFixes https://github.com/square/okhttp/issues/4743n

Fix flaky CallTest.recoverWhenRetryOnConnectionFailureIsTrue_HTTP2MockWebServer sometimes enforces the DISCONNECT_AFTER_REQUEST policy before the client executes exchange.finishRequest(). As a result, Http2Writer.flush() is called on a closed Http2Writer and throws. This causes a RequestFailed event to be emitted instead of the expected ResponseFailed.nnThis change enforces the de-facto sequence in most runs, where the policy is applied only after the client finishes writing the request.nnFixes https://github.com/square/okhttp/issues/4704n

TaskRunner, an abstraction over ExecutorServiceI want to tighten up our executors for a few reasonsn - Fix daemon vs. non-daemon problemsn - Fix code unloading problemsn - Be able to wait for async work to complete in tearDown()n - Fewer threads for pongs, acks, and window updatesnnThis shouldn't be too much to layer on top of ExecutorService, butnit is not easy to do with those APIs alone.nnThe underlying motivation is to make scheduling work easier innHttp2Connection, which will help with differentiating betweenndead streams and dead connections.nnhttps://github.com/square/okhttp/issues/3146n

TaskRunner support for shutting down queuesShutting down queues makes it easier to implement HTTP/2nshutdown because we can enqueue everywhere and centralizenthe logic that decides whether we're shutdown or not.nnUse this new functionality to implement HTTP/2 on task queues.nIt's mostly a drop-in replacement, though opting-into cancelnlooks like a mistake when it's what we do most of the time.nnWhen testing this the OkHttpClientTestRule was failing becausentasks were incomplete. I was puzzled by this until I realizednthat the OkHttpClientTestRule performs that validation beforenwe stop the MockWebServer. I changed MockWebServer to have itsnown TaskRunner and that made the problem go away.n
